Options Pricing using Machine Learning Models¶

This project aims to predict option prices using various machine learning models and I intend to implement and experiment with different algorithms. At the moment, it employs the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm for its prediction task. However, I am open to using different models as I gain more experience and knowledge. Furthermore, the project also uses the Black-Scholes formula to calculate theoretical prices which is used as a benchmark to compare the predictive ability of the machine learning model. My goal is to create a model that has predictive abilities comparable to the Black-Scholes formula.

Data Source and Features¶

We are using options chain data obtained from OptionsDX for all of 2022.

Features names that are prefixed with "C_" indicate it is a call and "P_" indicates it is an option

STRIKE_DISTANCE: Distance from the strike price to the underlying price

STRIKE: Strike price

DTE: Days until the expiration of the contract

ASK: Ask price

BID: Bid price

IV: Implied volatility

DELTA: How much the option price changes for every $1 change in the options price

GAMMA: How much the delta changes for every $1 change in the options price

VEGA: How much the option price changes for every 1% in the implied volatility

THETA: How much the option price decreases in value every day

RHO: How much the option price changes for every 1% change in interest rates

IV: Implied volatility of the options

LAST: Last traded price, which we are modeling to predict

Data Preprocessing¶

After chunking the data from the csv file and appending it to the dataframes, we then start cleaning the data by dropping any missing values. We then split the data into features (X) and the target variable (y) for the both calls and puts. The data is split to be 80% training and 20% testing. Before applying the machine learning models, the feature variables are standardized and normalized using StandardScaler.

Data Analysis¶

Next, we graph the data and find the descriptive statistics to provide an understanding of the underlying features that are being used to train the model. We are visualizing the data using matplotlib and pyplot. We have plotted a histogram for each of the features in the calls and puts.

Model Training and Evaluation¶

We use the training dataset with roughly 80000 records for each CSV to train both the model for both the calls and puts. Next, we apply the Black-Scholes equations with the data in order to server as a basis for comparison. Both the KNN model and the Black-Scholes models are evaluated using with mean squared error (MSE), mean absolute error (MAE), and residuals squared (R^2). The residuals for each model are plotted in a residual graph.

Data Visualization¶

We use Matplotlib to visualize the data as well as compare the outputs of the model between the actual values. This provides an intuitive understanding of the performance of our model. We are also visualizing the errors of the predictions in order to better understand the model's performance. Finally, we are using the Black-Scholes model as a benchmark to compare the predictive ability of the model.

# Formula for equation as shown above
def black_scholes(row, option='call'):
    S = row['UNDERLYING_LAST'] # Underlying asset price
    K = row['STRIKE'] # Strike price
    T = row['DTE'] / 365.0 # Time to maturity in years
    r = 0.01 # Risk-free rate (We are going to assume it is 1%)
    σ = row['C_IV'] if option == 'call' else row['P_IV'] # Implied volatility

    d1 = (np.log(S / K) + ((r + ((σ ** 2) / 2)) * T)) / (σ * np.sqrt(T))
    d2 = d1 - (σ * np.sqrt(T))
    
    if option == 'call':
        return stats.norm.cdf(d1, 0.0, 1.0) * S - stats.norm.cdf(d2, 0.0, 1.0) * K * np.exp(-r * T)
    elif option == 'put':
        return stats.norm.cdf(-d2, 0.0, 1.0) * K * np.exp(-r * T) - stats.norm.cdf(-d1, 0.0, 1.0) * S
    
# Since the csv files are relatively large (~10 GB each), we are chunking the data and processing the records chunk by chunk
# Then we are concatenating it to the pandas dataframe
def load_and_process(filename, chunksize=10**6):
    # We are predicing C_LAST and P_LAST
    relevant_call_features = ['C_LAST', 'UNDERLYING_LAST', 'DTE', 'STRIKE', 'STRIKE_DISTANCE', 'C_BID', 'C_ASK', 'C_IV', 'C_DELTA', 'C_GAMMA', 'C_VEGA', 'C_THETA']
    relevant_put_features = ['P_LAST', 'UNDERLYING_LAST', 'DTE', 'STRIKE', 'STRIKE_DISTANCE', 'P_BID', 'P_ASK', 'P_IV', 'P_DELTA', 'P_GAMMA', 'P_VEGA', 'P_THETA']
    
    columns = pd.read_csv(filename, nrows=0).columns.tolist()
    print("Columns:", columns)

    # Initial empty dataframes
    df_calls = pd.DataFrame()
    df_puts = pd.DataFrame()

    for chunk in pd.read_csv(filename, skiprows=1, header=None, names=columns, chunksize=chunksize):
        chunk_calls = chunk[relevant_call_features]
        chunk_puts = chunk[relevant_put_features]

        # We know if it is a call or put if the bid value is not 0
        is_call = chunk_calls['C_BID'] != 0.0
        is_put = chunk_puts['P_BID'] != 0.0

        # Appending the chunked data to the data frames
        df_calls = pd.concat([df_calls, chunk_calls[is_call]], ignore_index=True)
        df_puts = pd.concat([df_puts, chunk_puts[is_put]], ignore_index=True)

    # Dropping the empty rows
    df_calls = df_calls.dropna(subset=['C_LAST'])
    df_puts = df_puts.dropna(subset=['P_LAST'])

    # Drop Nan values as well
    df_calls = df_calls.dropna()
    df_puts = df_puts.dropna()

    # Drop invalid rows that have negative implied volatility
    df_calls.drop(df_calls[df_calls['C_IV'] < 0].index, inplace=True)
    df_puts.drop(df_puts[df_puts['P_IV'] < 0].index, inplace=True)
    df_calls.drop(df_calls[df_calls['C_LAST'] == 0].index, inplace=True)
    df_puts.drop(df_puts[df_puts['P_LAST'] == 0].index, inplace=True)

    # Splitting the data by 80% training and 20% testing
    train_calls, test_calls = train_test_split(df_calls, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
    train_puts, test_puts = train_test_split(df_puts, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
    
    
    return train_calls, test_calls, train_puts, test_puts

train_calls, test_calls, train_puts, test_puts = load_and_process('spy_eod_2022.csv')

Problems and Challenges I Came Across¶

The first problem I encountered was cleaning the data and processing such a large 10+ GB csv file into a Pandas dataframe. I solved this using Pythons functions to preprocess the CSV file itself and clean the headers and records. Then I processed by chunking the data so that it can be processed incrementally instead of all at once.

There were many invalid or uncleaned records that had impossible values such as negative implied volatility. There were also problems with too little significant figures and numbers being cut off as 0. For example, many last option prices were 0 when that should be incredibly unlikely.

I had quite a bit of difficulty in visualizing the data as I didn't know how to represent the inputs and outputs in a meaningful way. Other than the typical describe and head functions as well as scatterplots and histograms, I had little experience with making understandable plots. Fortunately, I have found inspiration from other data science and machine learning projects to help me throughout the process.

The problem that took me the longest to figure out was forgetting to scale the output of the Black-Scholes prices after having already scaled the inputs of that are placed into the equaiton. This led it to have incredibly high Mean Squared Errors. The reason it took me so long to determine was that I was not sure whether the problems were from incorrect implementation of the functions or from having misrepresentative data.

Conclusion¶

After a great deal of trial and error, I was able to get a model that was comparable with the Black-Scholes equation. However, the model has access to much more information with the Greek's that the Black-Scholes did not account for. I learned a great deal about the data science process such as data wrangling and data preprocessing as well machine learning techniques. I also came across several unexpected difficulties that I had to play around with the data in order to properly clean. I also learned about many of the limitations with the machine learning models and black-scholes equation. I believe that the next best steps forward are improving the data visualization, providing more accurate and verified data, and finally using and experimenting with different models.

Future Areas of Improvement¶

  • Experiment with different models and use more complex algorithms
  • Find the best hyperparameters to improve the predictive ability of the model and reduce MSE
  • Add much more data (Obtain options chain data from OptionsDX from several more years)
  • Find other data sources to validate or replace current data source
  • Improve data visualization
